# This is a simple visualization of word counts
#   made from the text of this very RMarkdown file itself -
#   giving a very rough but fun look at how we can describe me.
#
#   This file isn't a great source of data, since it is
#       not somehow representative, but of course manufactured
#       to tell a story.
#
#   But it is a nice example of
#       qualitative visualization & analysis,
#       and we can say it certainly shows the words I have
#       used to describe myself in a resum√© over time.
#
#   I'm ready to build up the count of "evaluation"!!
#
##################################################################.

# # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # #
#--- this use of wordcloud2 & tm & tidytext
#           taken from https://datatricks.co.uk/wordclouds-in-r
# # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # # #

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(readr))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(wordcloud2))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(tm))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(tidytext))

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(htmlwidgets))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(webshot))


#--- Take all the text from this file itself ---
myFileText <- readr::read_file("index.Rmd")

#--- Turn it into a "Corpus" object for use with tm and then wordcloud2 ---
preDocs <- VectorSource(myFileText)
docs <- Corpus(preDocs)


#--- We then clean out unhelpful characters and words with tm before counting frequencies ---

    #-- Use tm to remove characters we don't want to count --
docs <- tm_map(docs, removePunctuation) #remove punctuation
docs <- tm_map(docs, removeNumbers) #remove numbers

    #-- Use tm to convert all to lowercase because we won't consider capitals as separating words --
docs <- tm_map(docs, tolower) #convert all characters to lower case

    #-- Go ahead and remove the standard exclusion words - "stopwords" - according to tm --
docs <- tm_map(docs, removeWords, stopwords("english")) #remove common words

    #-- And then I'll also remove other words dominating the frequency count that aren't interesting --

        #- manually remove these high-frequency words that are just keywords from the markdown & styling -
myManualExclusions <- c("onetabxs","onetabns","clicksummary","summarymore","margintoppx","sansserif","tajawal","summaryclick","fontsize","marginbottompx","marginleftpx","stylewidth","tight","borderleftwidth","columns","fontsizepx","lineheight","small","bbpnol","marginbottom","fontweight","margintop","navtabs","normal","width","borderbottomcolor","borderbottomwidth","flex","fontfamily","part","onetab","tmmapdocs","docs","myplot","styledisplay","size")
        #- manually remove these high-frequency words that are simply not descriptive or redundant to others -
myManualExclusions <- c(myManualExclusions, "I","click","using","developed","designed","‚Äì","‚Äî","‚Äì","new","contractor","jan","feb","mar","apr","may","jun","jul","aug","sep","oct","nov","dec","work","ohio","including","program","summary","center","chapter","well","around","first","successfully","take","taking","year","event","insurance","nationwide","state","stored","massage","truemt","mix","present","north","brands","columbus","certified","amtaohio","end","expesite","firms","lets","many","two","words","use","time","remove","used","across","america","color","difficult","every","document","kentucky","fulltime","also","career","classroom","committee","towards","groups","several","file","made","took","output","parttime","occasional", "different", "important", "implemented", "office", "working", "therapy", "therapist", "certificate", "continuing", "hub", "apps")
        # !! - manually remove these high-frequency words that are technology keywords I'm intentionally skipping -
myManualExclusions <- c(myManualExclusions, "server","sql","data","ssis","tsql","asp","web","com","net","google","application","aspnet","xml","etl","forms")
            # ^^^ this last one is where I'm "cheating" a little to drop technology keywords from my past

    #-- And use my manual exclusion list now against the Corpus --
docs <- tm_map(docs, removeWords, myManualExclusions) #remove any additional specific words

    #-- Finally, we also remove whitespace --
docs <- tm_map(docs, stripWhitespace) #remove whitespaces



#--- Then finally we use tm to create the matrix of words and frequencies ---
dtm <- DocumentTermMatrix(docs)

#--- And then with tidy we convert the document term matrix into a dataframe and sort by frequency ---
df <- tidy(dtm)
df <- df[order(-df$count),c(2,3)]



#--- Last, I further refine the list to the top 80, __except__ for the first two ---
    #-- !!! I manually drop the first two rows, which are mystery multibyte(?) characters that come out as long dashes --
dfOut <- df[3:NROW(df),]
    #-- and then let's take the top 80, which keeps us at a manageable point of frequencies of at least 6 --
dfOut <- dfOut[1:80,]


#--- And now we can output the cloud !!! ---
wordcloud2(data = dfOut, shape = 'circle', size=.25)

#--- Let's have ggplot explicitly for reference ---

#--- Then let's declare our simple plot of vertical lines! ---
myPlot <- ggplot(data=careerAreaTimelines)
myPlot <- myPlot + geom_line(aes(x=1, y=evaluation), size=3, color="#037F8C")
myPlot <- myPlot + geom_line(aes(x=2, y=sacl), size=3, color="#F25757")
myPlot <- myPlot + geom_line(aes(x=3, y=software), size=3, color="#668C4A")
myPlot <- myPlot + geom_line(aes(x=4, y=teaching), size=3, color="#205459")
myPlot <- myPlot + geom_line(aes(x=5, y=massage), size=3, color="#F28F38")

#--- Now we'll set the axis information for the 5 career areas ---
myPlot <- myPlot + scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(1,5,by=1), labels=c("evaluation", "social action", "software", "teaching", "massage"), limits=c(.5,5.5), expand = c(0,0), position = "top")
#--- And also set the scope of the year axis ---
myPlot <- myPlot + scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(2005,2021,by=1), limits=c(2005.4,2021.7), expand=c(0,0))

#--- And last we'll adjust the appearance ---
myPlot <- myPlot + theme(
                            plot.background = element_rect(fill = "#BFD5E3"),                        
                            plot.margin = margin(t=20,b=20,r=20,l=20),
                            axis.title.x = element_blank(),
                            axis.title.y = element_blank(),
                            panel.grid.minor.x = element_blank(),
                            
                            axis.text.x.top = element_text(size=30, angle=90, margin=margin(b=15), vjust=.33),
                            axis.text.y = element_text(size=35, margin=margin(r=15))
                    )

#--- Then finally display the plot! ---
